Applying pySCA for any protein of interest, part II¶

Created by Thuy N. Nguyen, 191202¶

These notebooks are intended to supplement pySCA documentation here: https://ranganathanlab.gitlab.io/pySCA/install/

The goal of these general_pySCA usage notebooks is for users to be able to easily apply SCA to their protein of interest. In the first part, the user processed their multiple sequence alignment, performed the SCA calculations, and evaluated whether or not their MSA is appropriate for further analysis and sector identification.

In this second part, the user will take the variables from part I to (1) decompose the matrix of co-evolution ($C_{ij}$) using linear algebra methods: Eigendecomposition and Independent Components Analysis (ICA), (2) use this decomposition identify the most significantally co-evolving groups of amino acids, and (3) identify which species contribute to these co-evolving amino acids using a linear algebra method called the Singular Value Decomposition.

4. Identify significant positions in each top independent component (IC)¶

Like in each EV, each IC is an array of N positions. Each value is the contribution of the a given amino acid's positional correlation to the IC.

To define the positions with significant contributions to each of the independent components (ICs), we make a empirical fit for each IC to the t-distribution and select positions with greater than a specified cutoff on the CDF. We choose $p=0.95$ as our cutoff. Note that since some positions might contribute significantly to more than one IC (an indication of non-independence of ICs), we apply a simple algorithm to assign such positions to one IC. Specifically, we assign positions to the IC with which it has the greatest degree of co-evolution.

In [82]:
# plot histogram of each IC
for k in range(Dsect['kpos']): #iterate through each significant IC 
    
    # determine number of bins for the histogram based on interquartile range
    iqr = stats.scoreatpercentile(independentComponents[:,k],75) - stats.scoreatpercentile(independentComponents[:,k],25)
    binWidth = 2*iqr*(len(independentComponents[:,k])**(-0.33))
    nBins = int(round((max(independentComponents[:,k]) - min(independentComponents[:,k]))/binWidth))

    #plot histogram of values in each IC
    plt.figure()
    h_params = plt.hist(independentComponents[:,k], nBins,color = 'navy')
        #output of histogram are the height of each bin and their x-positions 
    
    # plot t-distribution of each IC 
    x_dist = np.linspace(min(h_params[1]), max(h_params[1]), num=100)
    plt.plot(x_dist,Dsect['scaled_pd'][k],'r',linewidth = 2)  


    # plot defined significance cut-off 
    plt.plot([Dsect['cutoff'][k],Dsect['cutoff'][k]],[0,max(h_params[0])+10],'--m',linewidth = 3)
    plt.title('IC'+str(k+1))
    plt.ylabel('number of positions')
    plt.xlabel('$\~{V}^P_%i$'%(k+1),fontsize=20)

The histogram of each IC is in navy. The fitted t-distribution is the red line. The significance cutoff is the magenta dashed line. The amino acid positions in the protein that with significant signals of co-evolution lie to the right of the cutoffs in each IC. Let's print out significant positions in each IC. 5. Defining sectors¶

To define protein sectors, we examine the structure of the SCA positional correlation matrix with positions contributing to the top independent components (ICs) ordered by weight. This provides a basis to determine/interpret which ICs are truly statistically independent (defining an independent sector) and which represent hierarchical breakdowns of one sector.

Plot the positional correlations, $\tilde{C}_{ij}$, but positions are ordered by contribution to the top ICs.¶

In this figure, the positions within each IC are separated by a thick white line.

A sector is the sub-set of ICs that are not fully indepenent from each other. Signal in the off-diagonals will indicate coupling between a given pair of ICs. Note, that defining sectors in this way is heurisitc.¶

For the serine protease, the off-diagonals have relatively little signal. This means that serine protease has 6 sectors, one for each IC.

For dihydrofolate reductase, each IC is not fully independent from one another. This means that DHFR has a single sector composed of all significant positions in all of its ICs.

Grouping ICs into sector(s)¶

In [115]:
#### DEFINE ICs and colors FOR EACH SECTOR ####################################################################
sector_groups = [[0],[1],[2],[3],[4],[5]]
colors = [0.4,0,0.7,0.15,0.9,0.5] #s1 = green, s2 = red, s3 = blue, s4 = orange, s5 = hot pink, s6 = cyan
##############################################################################################################

sectors = []
#Create class, s, for each sector that goes into the list, sectors.
    # Each class has two objects, col and items. 
    #s.col - color for the sector
    #s.items - positions in each IC. Ordered from highest to lowest signal. 

for n,sectorICs in enumerate(sector_groups):  #1. iterate through each sector
    s = sca.Unit() #2.initialize class
    
    all_items = list() #3. initialize list of position indicies
    all_Vp = list() #4. initalize list of positional correlations in each IC 

    for i in sectorICs: #5. itereate through each IC in the sector 
        all_items = all_items+Dsect['ics'][i].items #6. add indexes of positions each IC in the sector to the list
        all_Vp = all_Vp+list(Dsect['ics'][i].vect) #7. add positional correlations in the IC to the list 
    
    svals = np.argsort(all_Vp) #8. sort positions in sector from gretaest to lowest positional correlation 
    s.items = [all_items[i] for i in svals] #9. sort indicies of positions accordingly and save this object to the class. 
    s.col = colors[n] #10. save color for the sector as an object to the class
    sectors.append(s)#11. save class to the list of sectors

6. Studying the basis of positional correlations with sequence correlations and functional annotations.¶

The sequence correlations are directly related to the positional correlations by the single value decomposition (SVD).¶

The sequence similarity matrix is decomposed with eigendecomposition and then rotated with $W$,the multiplier that maximized the differences between positional correlaations. This allows for each independent component in the sequence space ($U^{p}_{k}$) to be directly interpretable alongside each indepednent component in the positional space ($V^{p}_{k}$).

For the purposes of this script, I will show how you can analyze sequence correlations according to taxonomic information that was added to the headers of each sequence of the MSA with annotateMSA. These headers are stored in Dseq['hd']. Note: The following section parses custom headers for the MSA of serine protease, S1A. This parsing must be customized according to the features of each sequence you would like to study in detail.

STEP 1. Parsing sequence annotations into dictionaries.¶

Each sequence in your alignment with a header is stored in Dseq['hd']. In this example, we will parse the headers of the MSA for serine protease, 's1Ahalabi_1470_nosnakes.an'.

NOTE THAT FOR THE S1A ALIGNMENT, THE FORMATTING OF THE HEADER LOOKS LIKE THIS:

>>>'gi|giNumber|vertebrate or invertebrate|cold or warm blooded|species name|level 0 group|level 1 group|level 2 group|level 3 group'

NOTE THAT FOR THE PFAM DHFR ALIGNMENT, THE FORMATTING OF THE HEADER IS DIFFERENT:

>>>'giNumber|protein name and or EC ID|species name|phylogenetic level 0 group, level 1 group, level 2 group, level 3 group'

You will need to customize how these data are parsed according to the annotations you are interested in studying.*

In [108]:
### S1A SERINE PROTEASE ###########################################################################################
# INITIALIZE dictionaries for the three general classes of information in the headers
annot = dict() #phlogenetic categorization of each sequence
spec = dict() #species information for each sequence
vert = dict() #the sequence comes from an vertebrate or invertebrate

# to vert, initalize a list for each category
vert['vertebrate'] = [] 
vert['not vertebrate']= []

#now iterate through each header, parse, and fill dictionaries
for headerix, header in enumerate(Dseq['hd']):
    
    splitHeader = header.split('__') #splits before vertebrate/invertebrate designation
    description = splitHeader[0] #defines giInfo string

    speciesID = splitHeader[0].split('|')[1] #species giNumber 
    annotationList = splitHeader[1].split('|') #splits annotation info on the right side of the double underscore into a list of strings
    
    speciesName = annotationList[2] #defines species identity
    annotationString = ','.join(annotationList[3:-2])
    
    annot[speciesID] = sca.Annot(description, speciesName, annotationString) 
    # for each species, an object was created and stored in annot with the speciesID as the key
        # to pull out information for each species in the dictionary, annot
        # 'giNumber' is a the gi number for the sequence as a string 
        # pull out description with: annot['giNumber'].descr 
        # pull out SpeciesName with: annot['giNumber'].species 
        # pull out annotationString with: annot['giNumber'].taxo

    if speciesName in spec.keys(): 
        spec[speciesName].append(i)
    else:
        spec[speciesName] = [i]
    
    if annotationList[0] in vert.keys(): #Does this sequence have a vertebrate/invertebrate identification?
        vert[annotationList[0]].append(i)

    # for each key in the dictionaries spec or vert, a list of indexes of the sequences in the MSA

In [103]:
def whatColorIsThis(scaColNum):
    #This takes any number encoding shown in sca.figColors() and 
    #converts it into a 3 number color code that matplotlib understands
    #Enter a number no greater than 1 
    
    if scaColNum >= 0 and scaColNum < 1:
        bgr = sca.colorsys.hsv_to_rgb(scaColNum, 1, 1)
    if scaColNum >= 1:
        bgr = [0.3, 0.3, 0.3]
    if scaColNum < 0:
        bgr = [0.7, 0.7, 0.7]
    return bgr

def makeAnnotationLegend(colorList,legendList):
    #this takes a list that contains your list of SCA color numbers and corresponding annotation list
    #allows you to make a legend! 
    for six,s in enumerate(colorList):
        plt.title('LEGEND')
        plt.plot(0,six,'o',color = whatColorIsThis(s),markersize=10,markeredgecolor ='k')
        plt.text(0.4,six-0.4,legendList[six],color = 'k',fontweight = 'bold')
    plt.xlim(-1,5)
    plt.ylim(-2,len(colorList)+2)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])

2. plot scatter plots of IC pairs. Highlight positions in their respective sectors¶

For these plots, you must use the function, sca.figUnits(xvalues, yvalues, list of elements)

  • xvalues = positional correlations contributing to IC on x-axis ($V^P_{x}$)
  • yvalues = positional correlations contributing to IC on y-axis ($V^P_{y}$)

  • list of elements = list of classes, one for each sector. Each class stores the objects, col and items.

    col is SCA color number for the sector

    items is index of positions to be highlighted with the sector color.

The question driving this analysis is: Can the distinctions between vertebrates and invertebrates and/or distinction between phylogenetic groups infer the functional or evolutionary differences between each Sector?

Along IC3, there is a split of correlations between vertebrates (orange) and invertebrates (blue). This split roughly corresponds to divide between blue sector and the remaining positions in the protein. This tells you that there is a feature in the blue sectors that may have emerged after vertebrates diverged from invertebrates. The phylogenetic families belonging to vertebrates and invertebrates recapitulate this distinction of positions in the blue sector emerging separately from the rest of the sequences in the alignment.

Along IC1 and IC2, it is clear that the positions in the red and green sectors are distinct from each other. Sequences belonging to a subset of vertebrates along IC1 show some separation from the remaining invertebrates and vertebrates. This subset of vertebrates appear to belong to the sequences highlighted in cyan, mammals! One interpretation is that the function of the positions in the red sector could have emerged in mammals.
